  "local_port": 35668,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can you use Roku to browse the internet?",
  "response": "Roku devices are primarily designed for streaming media content, and they do not natively support web browsing like a computer or smartphone. However, there are a few workarounds to browse the internet on a Roku device:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Use a Third-Party App**\n   - **Web Browser X** or **Poprism Web Browser**: Some third-party apps can be installed on your Roku device to enable basic web browsing. These browsers are limited in functionality compared to traditional browsers but can be used for simple tasks.\n     - Go to the **Roku Channel Store** on your device.\n     - Search for a browser app like **Web Browser X**.\n     - Install the app and launch it to browse the internet.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Cast or Mirror from Another Device**\n   - **Screen Mirroring**: You can mirror the screen of your smartphone, tablet, or computer to your Roku device, allowing you to browse the internet on your device and view it on your TV.\n     - Enable screen mirroring on your Roku device:\n       - Go to **Settings > System > Screen Mirroring** and enable it.\n     - Use the screen mirroring feature on your smartphone (e.g., **Smart View** on Samsung or **Cast** on Android) or computer (e.g., **Miracast** on Windows).\n   - **YouTube or Chrome Casting**: If you want to view specific web content, you can use the **Google Chrome** browser on your computer or smartphone and cast the tab to your Roku device.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Use a Smart TV with Built-In Browser**\n   - If your TV has a built-in web browser, you can switch to the TV\u2019s native interface to browse the internet instead of using the Roku platform.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Link Streaming Channels**\n   - Some Roku channels, like YouTube or Hulu, can display web-based content indirectly. For example, you can watch YouTube videos or access web-based streaming services through their dedicated Roku channels.\n\n---\n\n### Limitations\n- Roku\u2019s browser apps are not as feature-rich as traditional browsers (e.g., Chrome, Safari).\n- Navigation is often clunky using a remote control.\n- Screen mirroring may have lag or quality issues.\n\nIf web browsing is a priority, consider using a dedicated device like a computer, smartphone, or tablet.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
